Generate structures to support parts of: Generate structures to support parts of the model which have overhangs. Without these structures, such parts would collapse during printing.
Different options that help to improve b: Different options that help to improve both priming your extrusion and adhesion to the build plate. Brim adds a single layer flat area around the base of your model to prevent warping. Raft adds a thick grid with a roof below the model. Skirt is a line printed around the model, but not connected to the model.
Multiplier of the line width on the firs: Multiplier of the line width on the first layer. Increasing this could improve bed adhesion.
Spiralize smooths out the Z move of the: Spiralize smooths out the Z move of the outer edge. This will create a steady Z increase over the whole print. This feature turns a solid model into a single walled print with a solid bottom. This feature should only be enabled when each layer only contains a single part.
Treat the model as a surface only, a vol: Treat the model as a surface only, a volume, or volumes with loose surfaces. The normal print mode only prints enclosed volumes. "Surface" prints a single wall tracing the mesh surface with no infill and no top/bottom skin. "Both" prints enclosed volumes like normal and any remaining polygons as surfaces.
The speed at which travel moves are made: The speed at which travel moves are made.
The speed at which top/bottom layers are: The speed at which top/bottom layers are printed.
The speed at which all inner walls are p: The speed at which all inner walls are printed. Printing the inner wall faster than the outer wall will reduce printing time. It works well to set this in between the outer wall speed and the infill speed.
The speed at which the outermost walls a: The speed at which the outermost walls are printed. Printing the outer wall at a lower speed improves the final skin quality. However, having a large difference between the inner wall speed and the outer wall speed will affect quality in a negative way.
The speed at which infill is printed.
The speed at which printing happens.
The speed at which the filament is retra: The speed at which the filament is retracted and primed during a retraction move.
The length of material retracted during: The length of material retracted during a retraction move.

The thickness of the bottom layers in th: The thickness of the bottom layers in the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of bottom layers.
The thickness of the top layers in the p: The thickness of the top layers in the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of top layers.
The thickness of the walls in the horizo: The thickness of the walls in the horizontal direction. This value divided by the wall line width defines the number of walls.
The height of the initial layer in mm. A: The height of the initial layer in mm. A thicker initial layer makes adhesion to the build plate easier.
The height of each layer in mm. Higher v: The height of each layer in mm. Higher values produce faster prints in lower resolution, lower values produce slower prints in higher resolution.
The height difference when performing a: The height difference when performing a Z Hop.
Whenever a retraction is done, the build: Whenever a retraction is done, the build plate is lowered to create clearance between the nozzle and the print. It prevents the nozzle from hitting the print during travel moves, reducing the chance to knock the print from the build plate.
The speed of travel moves in the initial: The speed of travel moves in the initial layer. A lower value is advised to prevent pulling previously printed parts away from the build plate. The value of this setting can automatically be calculated from the ratio between the Travel Speed and the Print Speed.
The speed of printing for the initial la: The speed of printing for the initial layer. A lower value is advised to improve adhesion to the build plate.
Whether the machine has a heated build p: Whether the machine has a heated build plate present.
The temperature used for printing the fi: The temperature used for printing the first layer. Set at 0 to disable special handling of the initial layer.
The temperature to which to already star: The temperature to which to already start cooling down just before the end of printing.
The temperature used for the heated buil: The temperature used for the heated build plate. If this is 0, the bed will not heat up for this print.
The temperature used for the heated build plate at the first layer.

Enter the text you want to engrave. The: Enter the text you want to engrave. The maximum length of the text is 125 mm. When the text is too long, it will be shrunk automatically. Start a new line manually according to your needs.
Setting work origin is essentially findi: Setting work origin is essentially finding the best place for the engraved image in the X and Y directions and determining the distance (Z Offset) between the Engraving & Carving Platform and the Laser Module to acquire the smallest laser dot on the material for the most efficient use of the laser power and the best result. For the 200mW Laser Engraving Module, the Z Offset can be set by judging the size of the laser dot by eyes with low power. However, for the 1600mW Laser Cutting Module, this method is less accurate as the laser dot is too strong and less interpretable. To set the Z Offset more accurately, we can move the module to the position that is close to the optimal Z Offset (Offset A). The software will test the results from a few positions next to Offset A on the same material. The best result determines the best Z Offset.
in the Axes section to move the Laser Cu: in the Axes section to move the Laser Cutting Module to the position that is close to the optimal Z Offset (just like how you do with the 200mW Laser Engraving Module).
Set Work Speed and Power based on the ma: Set Work Speed and Power based on the material you are using. If you are using a piece of 1.5 mm wood sheet, it’s recommended to set the Work Speed to a value between 80 mm/s and 120 mm/s and set the Power to 100%.
Choose the position that can cut the mat: Choose the position that can cut the material the most smoothly or engrave the thinnest line and the software will set it as Z Offset. In this example, -2.0 should be the Z Offset.
